FROM gemma4:12b

# ── Hardware ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# num_ctx is 32768 (see Context below) for headroom. At 32K the model no longer fits
# 100% on the 8GB GPU, so num_gpu is left to AUTO-offload (~74% GPU / 26% CPU).
# num_batch 256 keeps the compute buffer small so auto-offload keeps as many layers
# on GPU as possible. (To run 100% on GPU instead: drop num_ctx to 16384 and add
# `PARAMETER num_gpu 99` — but that's too tight once memory + web tools are loaded;
# real sessions hit ~24K input tokens.)
PARAMETER num_batch    256
PARAMETER num_thread   16

# ── Context & generation ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# num_ctx 65536: raised from 32K because tool schemas + hermes-memory tools + tool
# outputs filled 32K fast, forcing pi to compact constantly. Gemma 4's sliding-window
# attention keeps the KV cache tiny regardless of num_ctx, so a bigger window costs
# little VRAM (and system RAM is plentiful). Trade-off: long sessions get slower per turn.
PARAMETER num_ctx      65536
PARAMETER num_predict  8192

# ── Sampling ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# temperature lowered 0.6 → 0.3 for decisiveness: at higher temps this 12B model
# tends to second-guess itself ("Wait… Actually… Wait…") in agentic loops.
PARAMETER temperature   0.3
PARAMETER top_p         0.95
PARAMETER top_k         40
PARAMETER repeat_penalty 1.05

PARAMETER stop "<end_of_turn>"

# ── Template: inherit Gemma's built-in chat template from the base model.
# (The previous custom template injected non-Gemma <|think|>/<channel|> tokens,
#  which made the model emit only a reasoning block and no actual content.)

# ── System prompt: coding focus only ─────────────────────────────────────────
SYSTEM """You are an expert software engineer acting as a coding agent.

Be decisive. Once you have enough context, take the next concrete action (call a tool or
make the edit) or ask one short question — do NOT deliberate at length, restate the
situation, or talk yourself in and out of decisions. Use tools to act rather than
narrating what you intend to do; if you say you will do something, do it in the same turn.
Keep responses concise.

When working on code:
- Read and fully understand all context before making changes
- Plan which files need to change before writing any code
- Write complete implementations — never truncate with "...", "rest of file", or placeholder comments
- Prefer editing existing files over creating new ones
- Write idiomatic, production-quality code for the language in use
- Handle errors explicitly; do not swallow exceptions
- When using tools, call one at a time and wait for the result before proceeding
- After changes, briefly note what tests or checks should be run"""
